T-Tests, a couple different ways

Is there a significant difference in body mass between male and female chinstrap penguins? (Use two-sided t-test)

chinstrap_ttest <- t.test(chinstraps_f, chinstraps_m)
chinstrap_ttest
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  chinstraps_f and chinstraps_m
## t = -5.2077, df = 62.575, p-value = 2.264e-06
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -569.7903 -253.7391
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  3527.206  3938.971
cohen.d(chinstraps_m, chinstraps_f)
## 
## Cohen's d
## 
## d estimate: 1.263061 (large)
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##     lower     upper 
## 0.7327341 1.7933879

You can see from the t-test the P-value allows us to reject null hypothesis You can see from the cohenâ€™s d test, that there is a large effect size

Are male chinstrap penguins significantly larger (in body mass) than female chinstrap penguins? (use one-sided t-test)

t.test(chinstraps_m, chinstraps_f, alternative = "greater")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
##

Remember the ANOVA test is robust to violations of the normality assumptions and the equal variance assumption. You have to look at the data and then also run the Leveneâ€™s test for equal variance. Generally, if the largest sample variance is <4x the smallest sample variance, the variances are close enough. Here, the largest sample variance is Chinstrap (33.1) and the smallest sample variance is Gentoo (15.2) which is only 2X less than the largest (within the <4x guideline).

Leveneâ€™s test for equal variance

Use with caution, has same problem as other hypothesis tests do â€“ larger sample sizes are more likely to show significance. If you get a result that shows significant difference, then check back to make sure the variance falls within the 4:1 guidelines.

leveneTest(flipper_length_mm ~ species, data = penguin_f)
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##        Df F value  Pr(>F)  
## group   2  2.9012 0.05782 .
##       162                  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

.05782 is above the .05 threshold, yes we can assume equal variance.

We have decided that a means comparison via ANOVA is appropriate from all the above data viz

One-way ANOVA

penguin_aov <- aov(flipper_length_mm ~ species, data = penguin_f)
summary(penguin_aov)
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## species       2  21416   10708   411.8 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   162   4213      26                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

You can see with the very high F value that there is high variance across the groups compared to the variance between groups. The p-value is extremely low and means we can reject the null hypothesis that the groups were actually drawn from populations with the same mean values. Now, we use a post-hoc test TukeyHSD to find the adjusted significant difference between each pair of groups.

TukeyHSD(penguin_aov)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = flipper_length_mm ~ species, data = penguin_f)
## 
## $species
##                       diff       lwr       upr     p adj
## Chinstrap-Adelie  3.940774  1.436275  6.445272 0.0007922
## Gentoo-Adelie    24.912376 22.790647 27.034105 0.0000000
## Gentoo-Chinstrap 20.971602 18.366227 23.576977 0.0000000

If you have very different sample sizes, variance, and overall unbalanced design, you would use a type III ANOVA with the car package:

First create linear model to find linear relationship

penguin_lm <- lm(flipper_length_mm ~ species, data = penguin_f)
pengiun_aov_t3 <- Anova(penguin_lm, type = "III")
pengiun_aov_t3
